Pattern Evaluation — 2026-03-23

Total classes/records counted: 44
Patterns identified: 4
Pattern density: 0.09 (4 / 44)
Grade (Decoupling & SOLID): C-

| Area | Types / Examples | Abstract vs Concrete | Pattern & Notes |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| ASP.NET Controllers (MVC) | OrdersController, ProductsController, InventoryController, PaymentsController, RefundsController, ReturnsController | All concrete controllers deriving from ControllerBase | Uses built-in MVC routing; logic is transaction scripts inside controllers, no service layer; coupling to EF Core.
| DTOs | OrderLineDto, CreateOrderDto, PaymentRequestDto, RefundRequestDto | Records; contract-only types | DTO pattern separates request payloads from entities; still no validation/service orchestration layer to enforce invariants.
| EF Core Unit of Work | RetailDbContext + `Database.BeginTransactionAsync` usage in payments/refunds/orders | Concrete DbContext only; no repository interfaces | Relies on EF Core's Unit of Work/transaction pattern; tight coupling to ORM, no abstraction for persistence.
| Inheritance (TPH) | Product → {PerishableGoods, LuxuryItems, DigitalDownloads}; StockLocation → {Warehouse, Store} | Base classes are concrete, not abstract | Single-table inheritance via discriminator; no polymorphic behavior/strategy; primarily a structural mapping pattern.
| Missing patterns | – | – | No Strategy/Factory/Repository/Observer; no interfaces/abstract classes for domain or services; controllers directly manipulate entities.

Key SOLID / Decoupling Observations
- Single Responsibility: Controllers mix HTTP handling with domain orchestration and persistence concerns.
- Open/Closed & Liskov: Inheritance hierarchies are structural but not behaviorally substitutable; base classes are concrete, risking misuse.
- Interface Segregation & DIP: Zero interfaces or abstractions for repositories/services; dependencies are concrete DbContext instances.
- Encapsulation: Anemic domain entities expose settable properties with no invariants; business rules live in controllers.

Recommendations (for improving grade)
1) Introduce interfaces and application services to separate orchestration from controllers; inject via DI.
2) Add repository interfaces (or queries via CQRS) to decouple persistence from domain logic.
3) Make base types abstract where appropriate and add polymorphic behavior or validation methods to enforce invariants.
4) Add domain events/observers for cross-cutting behaviors (inventory reservation, loyalty updates) instead of direct mutations in controllers.
